:: Guard's story2 {"position":"1800,600","size":"100,100"}
<div style="font-size: 30px; text-align: center">
**Guard:** Come closer, lad. If you’re to serve Signor Bentivoglio, you must know this blade. Not just any blade, a cinquedea, five fingers, for the width of the blade where it meets the hilt. See how it starts broad at the heel and runs quick to a narrow point? Short like a dagger, but it bites like a hawk. It lives on the left hip for quick work in close quarters.

**Pietro:** And what does it say here?

**Guard:** Look here at the hilt. That eagle is our house, and the Latin device NUNC MICHI means ‘now it is my moment.’
Along the blade you can notice shallow grooves, fullers. They aren’t empty, the smith cut fine inscriptions and tiny scenes into them.

**Pietro:** What do these images mean?

**Guard:** This is called an allegory. Here you can see fury that drives men forward, fortune that turns without warning, and virtue that inspires a knight to do good deeds. Those are not decorations, they’re reminders.
This is a luxury weapon, finely finished end to end, made to be seen and used. The style looks back to the ancients on purpose. One could say it is a little "Iliad". Signor Bentivoglio can wear it at his belt.

**Pietro:** It's a true work of art! Today this blade will bring good fortune to our lord!

**Guard:** Yes, that's right, but before I give it to you, let's check how well you've remembered everything.
